derivedFrom.description: Denouncing what they called a “serious deterioration” in the situation in the agriculture sector, the protesters declared a seven-day strike against government policies.  They also declared a moratorium on the sale of grain and beef, although they would allow the sale of perishables to stores.
derivedFrom.headline: Agriculture Sector Begins Seven-Day Strike against Government Policy; El campo inició un paro nacional de 7 días contra la política del Gobierno

derivedFrom.description: Ignoring the binding arbitration ordered by the Argentine Ministry of Labor, the union launched a new protest, this one for 72 hours.  They blocked fuel refineries and distributors in 18 provinces and demanded an “urgent” raise of 30%.
derivedFrom.headline: Truckers Stop Work Again and Halt the Distribution of Fuel; Camioneros volvió al paro y frenó la distribución de combustibles

derivedFrom.description: Workers from the dissident wing of the CTA (Workers’ Central of Argentina) demonstrated in front of the Pink House (presidential palace) to demand better wages.  The protest had the support of the General Confederation of Workers (CGT).
derivedFrom.headline: Work Stoppage by the Workers’ Central of Argentina with the Backing of Hugo Moyano of the CGT (Workers’ Union Center); Paro de la CTA con aval de Moyano
derivedFrom.comments: Changed source, title and desription; put links in proper column

derivedFrom.description: The demonstrators demanded an end to corruption, insecurity, and currency controls, as well as the Kirchner economic model.  They also called for an independent judiciary, respect for institutions, and the search for consensus.
derivedFrom.headline: Pot-Banging Demonstration Reaches the Plaza de Mayo with Anti-Government Slogans; El cacerolazo llegó a Plaza de Mayo con consignas contra el Gobierno

derivedFrom.description: The oil company Pan American Energy, operated by BP, shut down production due to a union protest against the company’s ignoring of a union demand.  The company pumps 100,000 barrels of crude a day, i.e., 15% of the crude production of the country.
derivedFrom.headline: Violent Takeover of an Oil Facility; Violenta toma de una planta petrolera
derivedFrom.comments: Changed source, title and decsription; put links in proper column

derivedFrom.description: The head of the General Confederation of Workers (CGT) leveled criticism at the “haughty” attitude of the president, Cristina Kirchner, especially her role during the dictatorship.  However, his tone was conciliatory, and he called for dialog.
derivedFrom.headline: In a Show of Force, Hugo Moyano Fills the Plaza de Mayo, Renews Claim on Profits, and Calls for More Dialog; En una muestra de poder, Moyano llenó la Plaza, renovó el reclamo por Ganancias y pidió más diálogo

derivedFrom.description:
With No Agreement on Salaries, Truckers Begin Surprise Work Stoppages
Salary talks collapsed, and the flow of goods was halted.   The truckers rejected the offer of an 18% hike in three increments as “absurd”.
derivedFrom.headline: With No Agreement on Salaries, Truckers Begin Surprise Work Stoppages; Sin acuerdo salarial, Camioneros arrancó con los paros sorpresivos

derivedFrom.description: An unofficial strike by air traffic controllers at the Aeroparque Airport causes flight diversions, delays, and long lines.  The “work to the rules” measures were to protests sanctions against employees as “arbitrary and discriminatory”.
derivedFrom.headline: Another Work Stoppage Complicates the Situation at the Aeroparque Airport; Otro paro complicó al Aeroparque

derivedFrom.description: In homages to two prominent victims killed by the dictatorship, the demonstrators criticized the government and the president.  They called the government “corrupt and complicit” in the crimes of the dictatorship.
derivedFrom.headline: Heavy Criticism Leveled at the Government in Homages to Kosteki and Santillan; Fuertes críticas al Gobierno en el homenaje a Kosteki y Santillán

derivedFrom.description: A group of wives of police officers from Oruro, La Paz and Potosi declared a hunger strike yesterday in the presence of the Vice Minister of Interior, under the Ministry of Government, after failing to receive a response to their demand: wage parity between the police and the military.
derivedFrom.headline: Hunger Strike Declared by Wives of Police Officers; Se declaran en huelga
derivedFrom.comments: Coded as nationwide because of the multiple areas.

derivedFrom.description: A group of interdepartmental transportation workers set up a roadblock on the Santa Cruz-Trinidad Highway (in the Pailon Sector, 45 km from Santa Cruz) due to their opposition to the opening of a new bus line that will provide service on this route.
derivedFrom.headline: Transportation Workers Block the Santa Cruz-Trinidad Highway; Transportistas bloquean en la carretera Santa Cruz-Trinidad
derivedFrom.comments: I agree with the performer.  It is about a bus route opposed by workers.  0161.

derivedFrom.description: Conflict in Colquiri, where confrontation about the possession of the mines of tin and zinc occurred last Thursday and Friday.
derivedFrom.headline: Colquiri Miners Engage in Dialog; Mineros de Colquiri dialogan

derivedFrom.description: The wives of the policemen started nationwide demonstrations demanding the wage parity between the police and the military.
derivedFrom.headline: Wives of Police Officers Begin Hunger Strike To Protest Lack of Response from Government; Esposas de policías inician huelga de hambre ante la falta de respuesta del gobierno

derivedFrom.description: A mutiny by Bolivian police officers demanding wage increases spread across the nation on Friday, with about 4,000 officers occupying their barracks. Protesters set fire to furniture and documents in a police office in La Paz, but the protest otherwise appeared peaceful.
derivedFrom.headline: Bolivia: Police Demand Better Pay

derivedFrom.description: Thousands of La Paz citizens gave an emotional welcome to the Ninth Indigenous March in Defense of Tipnis as it wound through the main streets of the capital city. The indigenous people avoided confrontations with elements aligned with the government, who organized a countermarch to support President Evo Morales
derivedFrom.headline: Ninth Indigenous March in Defense of Tipnis Avoids Provocation, Receives Support, and Now Awaits Dialog with the Government; IX marcha eludió provocaciones, recibió apoyo y ahora espera diálogo con el Gobierno

derivedFrom.description: They are protesting the fact that the government did  not consult them before installing a liquid separation at the oil facility nearby and had already begun oil exploration.
derivedFrom.headline: 300 Residents of the Community of Tarija Maintain Blockade of the Yacuiba-Santa Cruz Highway; 300 Comunarios de Tarija mantienen bloqueo de la carretera Yacuiba –Santa Cruz

derivedFrom.description: Coca growers from the Yungas region installed a blockade on the old road to Santa Cruz and a protest in the 14 of September Plaza.  Some have also engaged in a hunger strike. The cocaleros say that the government is not respecting coca in traditional zones.  If eradication continues, they say, they will strengthen the blockade and initiate other actions
derivedFrom.headline: Road Blocked in Yungas de Vandiola To Protest Coca Eradication Measures; Bloquean ruta por erradicación en Yungas de Vandiola

derivedFrom.description: Eight Prisoners at the San Pedro Prison, declared political prisoners, began a vigil and hunger strike in the yarad of the San Pedro Prison where they have been since June 19 at the offices of the UN located in La Paz, demanding that "political prisoners" who have been held for more than three years without being sentenced be released.
derivedFrom.headline: Eight Prisoners at the San Pedro Prison, Declared Political Prisoners, Begin Hunger Strike; Ocho reclusos del Penal de San Pedro declarados presos políticos inician huelga de hambre

derivedFrom.description: Scores of people took part in a demonstration to protest the poor state of development in the Province of Arauco.  The protest came after the president announced the “Arauo Moves Forward Plan”, which the protesters characterized as inadequate.
derivedFrom.headline: Twenty Arrests in Protest in the Province of Arauco; Decenas de detenidos dejó protesta en la provincia de Arauco

derivedFrom.description: Four students from different departments began a hunger strike on Thursday to pressure the authorities to find solutions in the face of accusations of administrative and financial irregularities at the institution
derivedFrom.headline: Four Students at the Universidad del Mar Begin Hunger Strike; Cuatro estudiantes de la Universidad del Mar inician huelga de hambre

derivedFrom.description: Demonstrators gathered to protest the visit of the King of Spain and the possibility of the signing of agreements that would be contrary to the interests of Chile.
derivedFrom.headline: Demonstrators Protest in Front of the Argentine Mint against the Visit by the King of Spain; Manifestantes protestan afuera de La Moneda por visita del Rey de España

derivedFrom.description: Hundreds of people protested Sunday near a theater where supporters of the former dictator Gen. Augusto Pinochet attended the screening of a pro-Pinochet documentary. The Chilean riot police used water cannons to disperse protestors outside a theater in the capital, Santiago.
derivedFrom.headline: Hundreds Protest Screening of Pro-Pinochet Film in Chile

derivedFrom.description: On Monday, members of the Arica truckers’ union blockaded the highway linking Chile and Perú in protest against fines imposed by Peruvian customs agents and what union members called a policy of harassment against Chilean freight trucks. Chilean taxi drivers who work the border crossing joined the protest, calling for an end to the long wait times that have hurt their business.
derivedFrom.headline: Truckers and taxi drivers cut route for mistreatment by Tacna Peruvian authorities; Camioneros y taxistas cortan ruta con Tacna por malos tratos de autoridades peruanas

derivedFrom.description: Tens of thousands of high school and college students took to the streets of the Chilean capital on Thursday to call for the end of public financing of private universities and other reforms to the country’s troubled educational system.
derivedFrom.headline: Chile: Thousands of students turn out for protest pressing for educational reforms
derivedFrom.comments:
Other cities in Chile, including Valparaiso and Concepción, held marches Thursday fighting for the same grounds.
(Santiago Times)
Coding as nationwide

derivedFrom.description: A group of demonstrators from the group Andha Chile began a protest this morning on the grounds of the Mint
derivedFrom.headline: Indebted Householders Now Begin Protest at the Mint; Deudores habitacionales ahora intentaron protestar en La Moneda

derivedFrom.description: Chilean Minister Beyer appeared at and supported the “March for Equality” which advocates the rights of homosexuals and same-sex couples.
derivedFrom.headline: Minister Beyer Takes Part in Multi-Day “March for Equality”; Ministro Beyer participa en multitudinaria “Marcha por la Igualdad”

derivedFrom.description: About 2500 protesters turned out to protest the profit motive in education.  Education authorities accused the student union of breaking promises it had made the day before.
derivedFrom.headline: 35 Arrests for Violations of Public Order in March Organized by Secondary-School Students; Marcha convocada por estudiantes secundarios dejó 35 detenidos por desórdenes públicos

derivedFrom.description: Private university students held a completely peaceful demonstration in downtown Santiago on 21 June against institutions profiting from higher education
derivedFrom.headline: March Organized by Federations of Private Universities Takes Place in Atmosphere of Complete Calm; En completa tranquilidad se desarrolla marcha convocada por federaciones de universidades privadas

derivedFrom.description: Starting at 00.01 hours today, a group of company employees of Tur Bus has mobilized to strike after failing to reach agreement with the company on the points of the new collective agreement.
derivedFrom.headline: Strike by Tur Bus Workers Halts 200 Trips throughout the Nation; Huelga de trabajadores de Tur Bus suspende 200 salidas a nivel nacional

derivedFrom.description: Members of the National University Union, protested in front of the Ministry of Labor to demand rights given bac to them by the court system.
derivedFrom.headline: Sitraunah pide requerimiento fiscal contra autoridades de la UNAH [Monetary Claim Requested against the Authorities of the National Autonomous University of Honduras]

derivedFrom.description: Workers claim the manager has not fulfilled his duty to improve working conditions and has performed below stantards in regards to managing the high demanding job.
derivedFrom.headline: Piden destituir gerente de la ENEE en Choluteca  [Employees of the National Electric Power Company Call for a Local Manager To Be Fired]

derivedFrom.description: On Sunday, more protests popped up around the country as the presidential candidates gathered in Guadalajara for the second and last scheduled debate before the election on July 1.
derivedFrom.headline: In Protests and Online, a Youth Movement Seeks to Sway Mexico’s Election
derivedFrom.comments: From LAHT article: Some 40,000 people, mainly young people, took to the streets of Mexico City, marching from the Zocalo, the capital’s main plaza, to the Angel of Independence monument in what organizers labeled the “Second National anti-Peña Nieto March.”

derivedFrom.description: On Sunday, more protests popped up around the country as the presidential candidates gathered in Guadalajara for the second and last scheduled debate before the election on July 1.
derivedFrom.headline: In Protests and Online, a Youth Movement Seeks to Sway Mexico’s Election

derivedFrom.description: Environmentalists and members of various social movements participated in a protest against the proposals discussed at the UN Conference on Sustainable Development. About 150 people attended the first act against the Rio +20, held in front of the State Environmental Institute (INEA).
derivedFrom.headline: Grupo protesta contra Rio+20 (Group Protests against Rio+20 Summit)
derivedFrom.comments: Note discrepancy in death count between news reports.

derivedFrom.description: About 300 indigenous people and environmentalists protested against the construction of Belo Monte hydroelectric dam in Altamira, PA. The demonstration occurred about 50 kilometers from the county seat, in the area known as a cofferdam, a kind of earth dam built on the Xingu River Consortium Builder Belo Monte.
derivedFrom.headline: Índios protestam em Altamira, PA, contra construção de Belo Monte (Indigenous People Demonstrate in Altamira, Parana, against the Construction of the Belo Monte Dam)

derivedFrom.description: Human rights advocates, environmentalists and members of the Jewish community protest in Rio de Janeiro against the participation of Iranian President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad in the upcoming Rio +20 summit.
derivedFrom.headline: Protesta en Río de Janeiro contra la presencia de Ahmadineyad en la Río+20 (Protest in Rio de Janeiro against the Presence of Ahmadinejad at the Rio+20 Summit)

derivedFrom.description: The National Coordination for the Memory, Truth and Justice held  a protest in the South Zone against a suspect accused of torturing leftist activists during the military dictatorship.  About 2500 people from various social movements attended the event, titled "Escracho."
derivedFrom.headline: Manifestantes fazem protesto contra suposto torturador no Rio (Demonstrators Protest against Accused Torturer in Rio)

derivedFrom.description: During the Rio+ Summit, some 100,000 activists, indigenous people and students march in the center of Rio de Janeiro, carrying banners, balloons and chainsaws to demand radical changes in the economy. Grievances range from Amazonian deforestation and the situation of indigenous peoples to wage conditions of public employees, to the claims of minorities.
derivedFrom.headline: Unas 100.000 personas marchan en Río para presionar a líderes en Rio+20 (100,000 People March in Rio To Exert Pressure on Leaders at Rio+20 Summit)

derivedFrom.description: Raoni Metuktire, a chief of the 5,000-member Kayapó tribe from the Brazilian states of Mato Grosso and Pará, led a 500-strong march of indigenous people with bows and arrows to the center where the three-day United Nations conference (Rio+20 Earth Summit) is taking place. They were barred by more than 100 police and soldiers from entering. Raoni and other indigenous activists have focused mainly on protesting construction of the Belo Monte dam in the state of Pará.
derivedFrom.headline: Stars of the Earth Summit

derivedFrom.description: Protest erupted in the Rio+20 conference centre on Thursday as civil rights groups carried out a "ritual rip-up" of a negotiating text that they condemn as a betrayal of future generations.
derivedFrom.headline: Rio+20 protesters perform 'ritual rip-up' of negotiated text
derivedFrom.comments: Number of protesters unknown

derivedFrom.description: The growers and sellers of corn are protesting the fact that corn is being imported while the corn output of the country is not being bought up, thus depressing prices.
derivedFrom.headline: Maiceros protestan afuera de Andipuerto en Guayaquil (Growers and Sellers of Corn Protests outside of Andipuerto in Guayaquil)

derivedFrom.description: In Tulcán disagreement persists on the new domestic gas distribution, which is done with a smart card. About 300 people who are affected by an alleged reduction of the gas quota held a protest outside the building of the Interior.
derivedFrom.headline: La reducción de cupos del gas genera protesta en Tulcán (Reduction of Quotas for Gas Causes Protests in Tulcan)

derivedFrom.description: About 20 young people conduct a sit-in demanding that the municipality does not use public funds in beauty pageants.
derivedFrom.headline: Organizaciones sociales juveniles realizan plantón en elección a Reina de Santo Domingo (Young People's Social Organizations Hold Stand-In Regarding Elections for Beauty Queens)

derivedFrom.description: Dozens of people gather to protest rising electric rates, while the Power Company of Guayaquil complains of growing deficits due to failure of customers to pay.  Protestors claim they don’t have the means to pay.
derivedFrom.headline: Planillas altas llevó a usuarios de eléctrica de Guayaquil a manifestarse con un plantón (High Bills Cause Users of Electricity To Demonstrate in Guayaquil with a Sit-In)
derivedFrom.comments: Event was held at 6:00 PM. Reports dated 5/25/2012 report on the event being scheduled not the actual event having taken place.

derivedFrom.description: Gathering at the airport, Colorado Party members protest trips made by the president, Fernando Lugo, who arrives that same day after a tour of Asia. Protesters argue that the president does not give priority to domestic problems.
derivedFrom.headline: Jóvenes colorados dan "bienvenida" a Lugo (Colorado Party Members "Welcome" President Fernando Lugo)

derivedFrom.description: 200 policemen arrived at the private property of the ex-senator of the Colorado Party, Blas Riquelme in Curuguaty, in the Canindeyú region of Eastern Paraguay, with the intention of evacuating the 100 campesino families that have been illegally occupying the land over the past three weeks. The evacuation soon turned violent, with shots being fired by both parties involved. The bloody confrontation resulted in the deaths of 16 people both police officers and campesinos. Allegedly, some of the campesino bodies showed ‘signs of execution’ such as gun wounds in the head or the mouth, throwing into controversy Filizzola’s claims that the police acted in self defence.
derivedFrom.headline: Un violento desalojo deja 16 muertos (Violent Eviction Leaves 16 Dead)
derivedFrom.comments: English headline added. Note discrepancy in death count between news reports.

derivedFrom.description: Peasant organizations, supporters of the Front Guasu and civic groups, intermittently closed Route 8 to the input branch of the district of San Juan Nepomuceno in protest against what they call "coup against President Fernando Lugo." The mobilized around 1,500 people, still occupy half road and announce that remain encamped on indefinite vigil in the square Pa'i Bogado. In parallel, a few thousand people in the square of the Child Jesus on May 3rd District, marched down the avenue of the same name by rejecting what they call the breakdown of the democratic process. In the town of San Francisco also about 300 people executed roadblocks for short spaces, which announced will continue indefinitely.
derivedFrom.headline: Campesinos cortan rutas en el sur del país (Peasant Groups Block Roads in the Southern Part of the Country)

derivedFrom.description: Approximately 2,500 people closed the Friendship Bridge linking Ciudad del Este (Paraguay) and Foz de Iguazu (Brazil). The demonstration was in support of Paraguay's president Fernando Lugo.
derivedFrom.headline: Manifestantes cerraron Puente de la Amistad (Demonstrators close Friendship Bridge (Puente de la Amistad))

derivedFrom.description: Protesting working hours, about 5000 workers took Antapaccay camp, dedicated to the oxidation of copper in the province of Espinar, Cusco. Police responded with tear gas and firecrackers, wounding one.
derivedFrom.headline: Subcontratistas de Xstrata dialogan con trabajadores que tomaron (Antapaccay Contractors of Xstrata Are Engaged in Dialog with the Workers Who Have Taken over Antapaccay)

derivedFrom.description: Workers in the mining company Buenaventura begin 12-day strike, demanding a wage increase.
derivedFrom.headline: Arequipa: Trabajadores de empresa minera Buenaventura llevan doce días en huelga (Arequipa: Workers at the Buenaventura Mining Company Begin 12-day Strike)
derivedFrom.comments: San Francisco, Paraguay is not listed on the World Gazetter

derivedFrom.description: The Trade Union of Education Workers of Peru (SUTEP) of the Arequipa region calls a 48-hour strike. An estimated 10,000 teachers participate.
derivedFrom.headline: Sutep inició protesta para exigir pago de deuda social (The Trade Union of Education Workers of Peru (SUTEP) Demands Payment of Social Debt)

derivedFrom.description: Administrative and health care workers in hospitals of the Ministry of Health began a 48-hour strike nationwide. They ask for a salary increase and that all contract workers be appointed.
derivedFrom.headline: Paro en EsSalud y Minsa afectó a miles de pacientes en regiones del sur peruano (Strike by EsSalud and Minsa Affects Thousands of Patients in Southern Peru)

derivedFrom.description: About 20 000 informal miners go on a 48-hour strike against government legislative decrees that seek to curb the illegal mining
derivedFrom.headline: Puno: mineros informales se concentran en plaza de armas para protestar (Puno: Unlicensed Miners Gather on Parade Ground To Stage Protest)
derivedFrom.comments: Event was held at 10:00 PM. Reports dated 5/30/2012 report on the event being scheduled not the actual event having taken place. This event could be considered an extension of 5/25/2012 protest; however, this protest, while organized by the same group, addresses a different grievance.

derivedFrom.description:
Riot police used tear gas Wednesday to break up a demonstration by college students in the Guatemalan capital.
...Students at San Carlos University demonstrated in solidarity with prospective teachers who were removed by force on Tuesday as they blocked a busy Guatemala City thoroughfare to protest proposed changes in teacher training.
derivedFrom.headline: Suspenden actividades en la Usac para evitar más incidentes (Students at San Carlos University Suspend Activities To Avoid Further Incidents)
derivedFrom.comments: note: details in the LAHT article are where I took my decription. The Prensa Libre translation isn't as clear as the LAHT article.

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) Normal Joint Institute students from West Justo Fufino Barrios, San Petro Sacatepequez, San Marcos, yesterday blocked the passage of vehicles at kilometer 248, the road to Quetzaltenango, in protest at the Ministry of Education (MINEDUC) seeks to extend the syllabus of teaching.
derivedFrom.headline: Estudiantes cierran carretera (Students Block Road)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) The anti-mining leader, Yolanda Oqueli was attache Wednesday afternoon while returning to his home after the protest against gold mining in San Pedro and San Jose Ayampuc Gulf.
derivedFrom.headline: Activistas repudian ataque contra lideresa de protesta antiminería (Activists Repudiate Attack against Leader of Anti-Mining Protest)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) Residents of Chichicastenango, Quiche, blocked, on Tuesday, the main entrances to the urban area of the city to protest against the politicization in the delivery of fertilizer.
derivedFrom.headline: Pobladores protestan contra politización en entrega de abono (Residents Protest the Politicization of the Delivery of Fertilizer)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) Students from three schools evacuated the headquarters of the Huehuetenango Department of Education, after contingents of the National Civil Police (PNC) on Monday posted themselves in front of that building
derivedFrom.headline: Estudiantes desalojan sede departamental de Educación  (Students Leave the Departmental Headquarters of the Ministry of Education)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) Residents of Santa Elena colonies 3 and The Lemon zone 18 denounced the lack of water for several weeks and ensure that the purchase of vital fluid affects the economy and quality or life...The protesters staged a protest and said that the capital city has not heard your requests to restore service and argue that only two water wells broke down.
derivedFrom.headline: Vecinos de zona 18 protestan por falta de agua (Residents of Zone 18 Protest the Lack of Water)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) For the second day and despite the release of the Ministry of Education (MINEDUC), have reached agreements, normalistas blocked the Interamerican Highway, in Huehuetenango, in rejection of the teaching curriculum change and expansion of three to five years of study.
derivedFrom.headline: Estudiantes instan a no acatar orden (Students Refuse To Heed Order)

derivedFrom.description: (The following is a Google Translation) Farmers in Santa Cruz del Quiche, Quiche, on Thursday protested the rate increase of public lighting in politicizing the delivery of fertilizer and abuse of authority of the mayor.
derivedFrom.headline: Campesinos protestan en contra de alcalde de Santa Cruz del Quiché (Peasants Protest against Mayor of Santa Cruz del Quiche)

derivedFrom.description: YoSoy132 movement of the Autonomous University of Puebla (BUAP) held a protest outside the local board of the Federal Electoral Institute in Angelopolis placed candles and paper stars as a means to request that the election on Sunday is done transparently
derivedFrom.headline: With candles, YoSoy132 BUAP requests the IFE-Puebla transparent elections
derivedFrom.comments: This event was added per VT comment

derivedFrom.description: A group of one hundred fifty members of the movement YoSoy132 marched through the streets of the historic center of the capital of Zacatecas, to present a series of actions to denounce irregularities in the electoral process of this first of July and convene the general public to participate through social networks to report any unlawful act intending to purchase or coercion of votes in the state.
derivedFrom.headline: Members manifest YoSoy132 in Zacatecas
derivedFrom.comments: This event was added per VT comment

derivedFrom.description: Police arrested six students of the movement YoSoy132, who was beaten and sprayed with pepper spray, accused of creating scandals, although apparently only did work as observers, informed colleagues of the victims.
derivedFrom.headline: Six members of the group YoSoy132 arrested
derivedFrom.comments: This event was added per VT comment

derivedFrom.description: To leave a message on the public to choose their leaders well this July 1, members of the movement YoSoy132 held a march. The venue was the Alamenda Mariano Escobedo. The march started at 18:30 with more than 300 participants.
derivedFrom.headline: YoSoy132 up for an election "clean"
